Aquaculture

Volume 530, 15 January 2021, 735732

A meta-analysis of the effects of replacing fish meals with insect meals on growth performance of fish

Author links open overlay panelKathelineHuaab
https://doi.org/10.1016/j.aquaculture.2020.735732Get rights and content

Highlights

â€¢

The effects of dietary inclusion levels of insect meals on fish growth performance were quantified through a meta-analysis.

â€¢

Fish can utilize moderate levels of insect meals to support growth performance comparable to fish meal-based diet.

â€¢

The effects of high levels of insect meals seem to be largely dependent on the insect species.

Abstract

Recognizing the importance of reducing fish meals in fish feeds to ensure the economic and environmental sustainability of aquaculture operations, there have been growing interests in using insect meals as a protein source in aquaculture feeds. Increasing number of studies have been conducted to test the effects of insect meals as substitutes of fish meals in feeds of various fish species with varying degrees of success. A meta-analysis was carried out to quantify the effects of insect meals on growth performance of fish. The meta-analysis indicated that in general low or moderate dietary incorporation levels of insect meals did not affect the growth of fish in comparison to fish meal-based diets. High dietary inclusion levels of different insect species appeared to have divergent effects on fish growth. While higher than 29% (Â±3%) dietary inclusion levels of black solider fly meals depressed the growth performance, yellow mealworm seemed to be well tolerated by fish. Full-fat and defatted black soldier fly meals did not seem to differ in their effects on fish growth performance but this should be viewed as inconclusive due to varying degrees of defatting and highly variable nutrient compositions of the insect meals. Overall the results suggest that insect meals are promising novel protein sources for aquaculture feeds. More research is warranted to further elucidate the various influencing factors on the effectiveness of the dietary inclusions of insect meals in aquaculture feeds, as well as to integrate and translate this information into practical feed formulations.

1. Introduction

One of the challenges faced by the aquaculture feeds industry is the substitution of fish meals by alternative protein sources due to the concerns about economic and ecological sustainability. There have been growing interests in using insect meals as a protein source in aquaculture feeds to alleviate the pressure from the fish meal usage. Insect meals are considered one of the most promising novel protein sources in aquaculture feeds, not only because of their favorable nutritional compositions especially in respect of protein content and amino acid profile, but also in consideration of the feasibility of increasing production to meet the demand for alternative protein sources in aquaculture feeds in connection with available processing technologies, cost and scalability (Hua et al., 2019).

Increasing number of studies have been carried out to test the effects of incorporating insect meals as substitutes of fish meals in feeds of various fish species. Varying degrees of success have been reported in the literature. While most studies recommended partial replacements of fish meals with insect meals, an increasing number of recent studies reported a successful 100% replacement of fish meal without compromising the growth performance of fish, even for carnivorous fish (Henry et al., 2015; Gasco et al., 2019; Hua et al., 2019; Nogales-Merida et al., 2019). However, the comparison of results from different studies is difficult due to differences in diet formulations, dietary nutrient compositions, insect species, fish species, and rearing conditions, etc. The 100% fish meal replacement level achieved by various insect meals in different studies corresponded to different inclusion rates of the insect meals in diets. For example, black soldier fly meal replaced 100% of fish meal at inclusion rates of 14.75â€“25% (Lock et al., 2016; Belghit et al., 2019) in diets of Atlantic salmon (Salmo salar), whereas the dietary inclusion rates to achieve 100% fish meal replacement were 10.6â€“14% for Jian carp (Cyprinus carpio var. Jian) (Li et al., 2017; Zhou et al., 2018). While a dietary inclusion level of 25% of yellow mealworm was equivalent to a 100% replacement of fish meal for rainbow trout (Oncorhynchus mykiss) (Rema et al., 2019), defatted yellow mealworm larvae were included at a dietary inclusion rate of 65% to achieve a 100% fish meal replacement for red seabream (Pagrus major) (Ido et al., 2019). It is evident that the fish meal replacement level is not an objective parameter in evaluating nutritive values of alternative ingredients such as insect meals, the same argument put forward by Hua and Bureau (2012) in evaluating plant protein sources. Because of the nature of this parameter, the fish meal replacement level achieved in one study cannot be extrapolated with confidence and thus becomes meaningless. A more meaningful investigation of the effects of insect meals should be based on the inclusion levels of insect meals in the diets. Furthermore, due to the varying degrees of success in incorporating different insect meals at various inclusion levels for a variety of fish species, it is necessary to synthesize the results from different studies, and more importantly to quantify the effects to facilitate the translation of the results into practical feed formulations.

Meta-analysis is a useful approach to extract and integrate information from different studies. This approach has been used to examine the issue of fish meal replacement by several protein sources in fish feeds (Drakeford and Pascoe, 2008; Sales, 2009; Hua and Bureau, 2012; Collins et al., 2013). However, so far this approach has not been applied to insect meals in fish feeds and the reviews on the effects of insect meals in aquaculture feeds have remained to be narrative and qualitative (Henry et al., 2015; Gasco et al., 2019; Hua et al., 2019; Nogales-Merida et al., 2019). There is a need to integrate and synthesize the experimental observations through a quantitative approach.

Therefore, the objectives of the present study were to conduct a meta-analysis to investigate the effects of insect meals replacing fish meals in fish diets on growth performance of fish.

2. Materials and methods

2.1. Literature search and dataset

The meta-analysis was carried out by following the principles of the Cochrane Handbook for Systematic Reviews of Interventions (Higgins et al., 2019) and the Preferred Reporting Items for Systematic Reviews and Meta-Analyses (PRISMA) Statement (Moher et al., 2009). A systematic search of literature was conducted in ISI WEB OF KNOWLEDGE (1965â€“2019) and SCOPUS (1970â€“2019) in December 2019. A combination of search terms and Boolean operators on insect species, fish, diet and growth were used to search Topic in ISI WEB OF KNOWLEDGE and Title-Abstract-Keywords in SCOPUS. The pre-specified criteria for a study to be included in the meta-analysis database were:

(i)

A control diet that contained fish meal;

(ii)

Experimental diets used insect meals as alternative protein sources for aquaculture fish;

(iii)

Studies investigated the effects of insect meals on the growth performance of fish. Specific growth rates (SGR) were either reported or could be calculated from the reported information;

(iv)

Fish were fed to satiation or excess to allow fish to achieve their growth potential. Studies were excluded in the case in which fish were fed to fixed rations but the satiation status was not reported.

The mean and standard deviation (SD) of SGR from fish meal control diet and insect meal experimental diet were either extracted or calculated from information reported in each study. The calculation of SGR was according to the following equation:SGR=lnFBWâˆ’lnIBWdÃ—100where FBW = final body weight, IBW = initial body weight, d = number of days.

Comparisons of treatments in the meta-analysis dataset were expressed as response ratio r, the ratio of parameters in experimental and control groups, which serves a measure of the proportionate change resulting from an experimental manipulation (Hedges et al., 1999; Borenstein et al., 2009). Effect sizes in the meta-analysis were obtained by the natural log-transformation of the response ratio r, the ratio of the mean SGR from the fish fed an insect meal diet to the mean SGR from the fish fed the fish meal control diet (Hedges et al., 1999):lnr=lnSGReâˆ’lnSGRcwhere lnr is the effect size log response ratio, SGRe and SGRc represent the means of the SGRs of the experimental diet and the control diet, respectively.

The variance of lnr was calculated as:SDe2+SDc2neSGRe2+ncSGRc2where SDe and SDc represent SD of the experimental diet and the control diet, respectively, and ne and nc represent the number of replications of the experimental diet and the control diet, respectively.

The meta-analysis was performed in JASP software (version 0.9.2, JASP Team, the Netherlands) using random effects models to account for the variation among the populations of studies. Between-study variance was assessed by I2 statistics (Higgins et al., 2003). Covariate analysis was carried out to investigate the effects of covariates including insect species, insect meal level, fish dietary habit (carnivorous vs. omnivorous), nutrient balance (whether the experimental diets containing insect meals were formulated to be isonitrogenous and isoenergetic to the fish meal control diets) on treatment effects. A further differentiation of individual fish species was not possible due to the limited number of data for carrying out a meaningful analysis for each fish species. The covariate insect meal level was a continuous variable, while other covariates were categorical variables.

Furthermore, to establish the optimal insect meal inclusion level, the relationships between incorporation levels of insect meal and response ratio r were analyzed by simple linear regressions and the following modified broken-line model (a horizontal line and a straight line with a decreasing slope; adapted from Robbins et al., 1979) in GraphPad Prism (version 7.03, GraphPad Software, San Diego, CA, USA):Y=L+UÃ—Xâˆ’Rwhere Y = response ratio r, X = insect meal incorporation level (% of diet), L = the ordinate of the breakpoint, R = the abscissa of the breakpoint, U = the slope of the line for X > R. By definition (Xâ€“R) is defined as zero when X < R.

3. Results

Fig. 1 illustrates the selection process for the studies that were included in the meta-analysis. The meta-analysis dataset consisted of 33 publications in peer-reviewed journals (Table 1). The most studied insect species was black solider fly (Hermetia illucens), accounting for 49% of the data, followed by yellow mealworm (Tenebrio molitor) representing 27% of the data, and housefly (Musca domestica) accounting for 14% of the data. Other insect species such as chironomids, crickets (Gryllus bimaculatus), mopane worms (Imbrasia belina) made up the rest of the data. A total of 17 fish species were investigated and 63% of the data were derived from carnivorous fish species. The incorporation levels of insect meals ranged from 0.05 to 75.6% of diets. The response ratio, the ratio of SGRs from insect meal diet and fish meal control diet ranged from 0.38 to 2.19, with 51% of the data showing a response ratio below 1.

Fig. 2 presents the forest plot of the treatment effect sizes of insect meals. The meta-analysis showed a mean effect size of âˆ’0.03 (confidence interval CI: âˆ’0.09 to 0.02, p = .208). This translated to a mean growth response of 97% (CI: 91% to 102%) of fish elicited by the insect meal diets and a non-significant difference from the growth response of fish to the fish meal control diets. The test of heterogeneity was significant at p < .001 and the I2 index was 98.73%, indicating significant variances between studies. A further meta-analysis revealed that covariates of insect meal levels and nutrient balance had significant effects (p < .001) on the effect size, and there were significant interactions (p < .05) between nutrient balance and insect species, as well as between nutrient balance and fish dietary habits. Further analyses were carried out on subgroups of insect species and nutrient balance. Among the insect species, only the groups of black solider fly (Hermetia illucens) and yellow mealworm (Tenebrio molitor) contained sufficient data to allow subgroup analyses.

The nutrient balanced dataset contained 84 data points, among which 39 data points (46% of data) showed inferior response ratios from fish fed insect meals in comparison to fish meals. The incorporation levels of insect meal ranged from 2.5 to 75.6% of diets. The meta-analysis on this group showed a mean effect size of âˆ’0.04 (CI: âˆ’0.09 to 0.01, p = .095), equivalent to a mean growth response of 96% (CI: 91% to 101%) elicited by insect meals in comparison to fish meals. Covariate analysis differentiated yellow mealworm from other insect species, but there was no significant difference in the overall treatment effect sizes between carnivorous and omnivorous fish species fed insect meals in the nutrient balanced dataset. Contrary to the findings from the full dataset that there was a significant linear negative effect of insect meals on the effect sizes, the effect of insect meal inclusion levels in the nutrient balanced dataset was quadratic. Fig. 3 presents the comparison of the relationship between insect meal inclusion level and the response ratio in growth rate for the full dataset (3a) and the nutrient balanced dataset (3b). For the full dataset, the relationship was best described by a linear equation (Fig. 3a):r=1.091âˆ’0.005Ã—%insect meal,R2=0.09,Sy.x=0.24

For the nutrient balanced dataset, the relationship was best described by the broken-line equation (Fig. 3b):r=1.001âˆ’0.021Ã—%insect mealâˆ’45.06,R2=0.45,Sy.x=0.10

The results suggested that when all data were considered, increasing insect meal levels depressed fish growth performance linearly. However, when the experimental diets and the control diets were isonitrogenous and isoenergetic, insect meals at levels below 45% (Â± 3%) had no negative effect on fish growth performance in comparison to fish meal control diets. However, at levels above this threshold, a significant reduction in growth performance was observed with an increase in insect meal levels.

The black soldier fly Hermetia illucens dataset contained 55 data points and the inclusion levels of black soldier fly meals ranged from 2.5 to 75.6% of diet. The results of the meta-analysis showed a significant negative effect of black soldier fly meals (p = .007). The mean effect size was âˆ’0.09 (CI: âˆ’0.16 to âˆ’0.02), which translated to a mean response of 91% (CI: 85% to 98%) growth performance of fish fed black soldier fly meals when compared to that of fish fed fish meals.

The results suggested that when the experimental diets and the control diets were comparable in macronutrient content, black soldier fly meals at levels below 29% (Â± 3%) had no negative effect on fish growth performance compared to fish meal control diets. However, at levels above this threshold, a significant reduction in growth performance was observed with an increase of black soldier fly meals in diets.

The black soldier fly meals in the nutrient balanced group were further differentiated into full-fat vs. defatted black soldier fly meals. The full-fat and defatted black soldier fly meals accounted for 47% and 53% of the nutrient balanced data, respectively. The results suggested thresholds of 33% (Â± 5%) and 25% (Â± 4%) for full-fat and defatted black soldier fly meals, respectively, beyond which a negative effect on fish growth performance was observed for insect meal diets in comparison to fish meal control diets. The effects of full-fat and defatted black soldier fly meals did not seem to differ.

Among the 30 data points in the yellow mealworm Tenebrio molitor dataset contained, only 6 data points showed negative effect sizes. The inclusion levels of yellow mealworm varied from 2.5 to 65% in the experimental diets. Meta-analysis revealed a non-significant effect of yellow mealworm in fish feeds on fish growth performance (p = .164). The mean effect size was 0.07, which was not significant different from 0 (CI: âˆ’0.03 to 0.17, p = .372). Covariate analysis suggested a non-significant effect (p > .05) of the inclusion level of yellow mealworm in experimental diets, irrespective of whether the experimental diets were formulated to be isonitrogenous and isoenergetic or not, which was corroborated by the linear regression of the response ratio on the inclusion level of yellow mealworm (Fig. 5a and b). As all yellow mealworms in the nutrient balanced group were full-fat meals, the differences between full-fat and defatted meals were not investigated for yellow mealworms.

4. Discussion

Among the various novel protein sources for aquaculture feeds, insect meals have attracted growing interests and an increasing number of studies on the effects of insect meals have been reported in the literature. While some studies succeeded in a 100% replacement of fish meal with insect meals even for carnivorous fish without compromising fish growth performance, a number of studies observed deleterious effects of high levels of insect meals on growth rates and feed efficiency in fish. The varying degrees of success in replacing fish meal by insect meals were reflected in the wide range of response ratios from 0.38 to 2.19 in the present study. 51% of data in the meta-analysis dataset showed a response ratio below 1, indicating about half of the experimental diets containing insect meals were inferior to fish meal control diets in supporting fish growth performance. In other words, about half the data suggested that insect meals could support similar or even better fish growth performance when compared to fish meal control diets in the literature. The meta-analysis on the full dataset further revealed a mean effect size that was not significant different from zero and a mean growth response that was not significantly different from 100%, which suggested that on average there was no significant difference between the growth performance fish fed insect meals and that of the fish meal control diets.

While the meta-analysis on the full dataset was indicative of the mean effect of insect meals on fish growth performance in the literature and confirmed the usefulness of insect meal in fish feeds, it is obvious that this analysis averaged out the possible influencing factors such as insect species, inclusion levels, dietary nutritional balance, etc. Therefore subgroup analyses were carried out to delineate the effects of these various covariates. An important factor to consider is the inclusion levels of insect meals, which could directly relate to the magnitude of physiological response. Establishing such doseâ€“response relationships or identifying a threshold beyond which negative effects might occur could provide useful information for the optimal incorporation levels of insect meals in practical feed formulation.

The present study demonstrated that the effects of insect meal levels on fish growth performance were influenced by dietary nutritional balance. When diets were imbalanced, increasing levels of insect meals had a linear negative effect on growth rate. On the other hand, insect meals in balanced diets had no adverse effect on fish growth rate up to a certain level, and a negative effect was exhibited only when insect meal inclusion levels reached a certain threshold. The regression analysis identified the threshold to be 45% for the full dataset. The discrepancies emphasized the necessity to ensure the nutritional adequacy and comparability of the experimental diets containing insect meals when comparing to the fish meal control diets.

The subgroup analysis also revealed differences among specific insect species in their effects on fish growth. High inclusion levels of black soldier fly (above 29 Â± 3%) seemed to depress the growth rate of fish when the experimental diets and the control diets were comparable in nutrient content, whereas yellow mealworm in fish diets at any levels did not appear to negatively influence growth rate. On the other hand, there did not seem to be differences between full-fat and defatted black soldier fly meals in their effects on fish growth performance when diets were nutrient balanced. The results strengthened the importance of ensuring the nutritional comparability of the experimental diets when evaluating the nutritive values of insect meals against fish meals.

So far the research on insect meals in aquaculture feeds has mostly focused on black soldier fly, common housefly, and yellow mealworm. Consequently it is likely that the observations of the full dataset were largely influenced by the data from the black soldier fly dataset due to the fact that black soldier fly accounted for nearly half of all data whereas yellow mealworm accounted for about a quarter of the data and common housefly accounted for one seventh of the data. Therefore, the results from the meta-analysis on the full dataset should be treated with caution. The subgroup analysis with different insect species is more meaningful than the generalized results across all insect species.

The differences in the effects between black soldier fly and yellow mealworm worth further investigation and illustrated the importance of identifying the optimal levels for different types of insect meals. In the present study the ranges of the inclusion levels of black soldier fly and yellow mealworm were similar: the inclusion levels of yellow mealworm varied from 2.5 to 65% in experimental diets, whereas the inclusion levels of black soldier fly meals ranged from 2.5 to 75.6% of diet. Therefore, the differences in the effects between these two insect species were likely a reflection of the true differences between the nutritive values of these two insect species rather than an artefact of discrepancies of dietary inclusion levels that were being investigated.

Nutritional values of black soldier flies and yellow mealworms reported in the literature show wide variations in nutrient compositions within insect species and it is thus difficult to compare across species. In general, yellow mealworms seem to contain higher crude protein and lower crude fat levels than black soldier flies. The levels of crude protein in black soldier flies were reported to be 36â€“59%, whereas the levels were 47â€“66% in yellow mealworms (Barroso et al., 2014; Makkar et al., 2014; Sanchez-Muros et al., 2014; Marono et al., 2015). Fat levels were reported to be 11â€“49% in black soldier flies and 15â€“43% in yellow mealworm (Makkar et al., 2014; Sanchez-Muros et al., 2014; Marono et al., 2015). The nutrient compositions of insect meals are highly dependent on substrates and processing methods. Defatted insect meals can contain up to 83% crude protein and low crude fat (Makkar et al., 2014). For example, defatted yellow mealworms were reported to contain 75% CP and 13% fat (Motte et al., 2019). On the other hand, ash content is usually quite high in black soldier flies in the range of 5 to 28% and rich in Ca and P, whereas yellow mealworms are relatively low in ash in the range of 3 to 6% (Barroso et al., 2014; Makkar et al., 2014; Sanchez-Muros et al., 2014; Marono et al., 2015). If the experimental diets are formulated with insect meals to replace fish meal without balancing nutrient composition across diets, the negative effects of insect meals on fish growth could be due to nutrient deficiencies and thus complicate the assessment and/or the comparison of nutritive values of the insect meals.

Nevertheless, in the subgroup analysis, even when the experimental diets were formulated to be isonitrogenous and isoenergetic to the fish meal control diets, divergent effects between black soldier flies and yellow mealworm at high levels were still found. At low or moderate levels of inclusions, both insect species could elicit growth performance similar to fish meal. This is in agreement with direct experimental data on comparing the effects of these two insect species at low or moderate inclusion levels in Siberian sturgeon and rainbow trout (JÃ³zefiak et al., 2019a, JÃ³zefiak et al., 2019b). It was observed that 15% or 20% of black soldier fly meal and yellow mealworm meal were able to support comparable growth in Siberian sturgeon and rainbow trout, respectively (JÃ³zefiak et al., 2019a, JÃ³zefiak et al., 2019b). The divergent effects from these two insect species at high inclusions levels necessitate investigations into factors beyond crude protein content or crude fat content and considerations of other factors that could affect the nutritive values, such as amino acids balance, fatty acids profile, nutrient digestibility, micronutrients and antinutritional factors.

Insect meals may contain high concentrations of non-protein nitrogen. It has been reported that 16â€“30% of total nitrogen in black soldier fly larvae is non-protein nitrogen (Janssen et al., 2017; Liland et al., 2017), and 12â€“23% of total nitrogen in mealworms is non-protein nitrogen (Janssen et al., 2017). It is possible that the crude protein levels in some studies were overestimated.

One of the non-protein nitrogen source is chitin. Chitin is a polymer of glucosamine and a nitrogen-containing compound in the cuticle of insects (Barroso et al., 2014; Henry et al., 2015). The effects of chitin from insect meals in fish diets appear to be complex. Chitin is generally considered anti-nutritional, and a compound that fish cannot digest (Rust, 2002). In addition to its negative effect on nutrient digestibility, chitin was also found to depress weight gain and feed conversion in tilapia (Shiau and Yu, 1999). On the other hand, research has demonstrated that low levels of chitin could act as immunostimulants (Henry et al., 2015; Henry et al., 2018b; Henry et al., 2018a). Several studies have observed prebiotic effects of chitin in the modulation of fish gut microbiota (Bruni et al., 2018; Terova et al., 2019).

The observed negative effects of insect meals on fish growth could be partly due to lower digestibility of the nutrients. A number of studies reported that incorporations of insect meals in fish diets could depress nutrient digestibility of the diets when compared to fish meal diets but conflicting results also exist. Belghit et al. (2018) observed lower digestibility of protein, amino acids, fat, and ash in diets containing 60% black soldier fly larvae meal than the fish meal diet in Atlantic salmon and ascribed the lower digestibility to the presence of chitin in black soldier fly larvae meal because chitin may interfere with the intestinal homeostasis in addition to a possible overestimate of crude protein due to non-protein nitrogen. Similarly, reductions in nutrient digestibility were also observed in diets of yellow catfish (Pelteobagrus fulvidraco) containing up to 16.9% black soldier fly larvae meal (Hu et al., 2017), and in diets of Siberian sturgeon (Acipenser baerii Brandt) juveniles containing 18.5% to 37.5% black soldier fly larvae meal (Caimi et al., 2020). On the other hand, up to 19.5% black soldier fly larvae meal in diets of European seabass (Dicentrarchus labrax) did not affect the digestibility of protein, lipid or energy (Magalhaes et al., 2017) and up to 30% black soldier fly larvae meal in diets of rainbow trout did not affect the digestibility of protein and energy (Terova et al., 2019). Renna et al. (2017) observed lower protein digestibility in rainbow trout at the dietary inclusion of 40% black soldier fly but not at 20%, which was attributed to the differences in chitin content from the different levels of insect meals in diets. Conflicting observations also exist for yellow mealworm meals. Dietary inclusions of yellow mealworm meal at 25% and 50% in gilthead sea bream (Sparus aurata) resulted in lower apparent digestibility of dry matter, crude protein and energy of the diets (Piccolo et al., 2017). However, Gasco et al. (2016) found that protein digestibility was even higher in diets of European seabass containing 25% yellow mealworm meal than fish meal control diet whereas there was no significant difference in lipid and carbohydrate digestibility, probably due to the presence of chitinase either from the fish or from the intestinal bacteria. Whether the differences in the literature reports were due to differences between black soldier fly larvae meal and yellow mealworm meal or a consequence of the presence/absence of endogenous chitinase among fish species remained to be investigated.

While the above-mentioned studies investigated nutrient digestibility in diets containing different levels of insect meal when comparing to fish meal control diets, studies on apparent digestibility of nutrients in insect meals as single ingredients have also revealed variable results. Protein and essential amino acids in black soldier fly larvae meal were reported to be highly digestible with digestibility values above 84%, whereas lipid was only 43% digestible in rainbow trout (Dumas et al., 2018). Protein and lipid digestibility of black soldier fly larvae meal were found to be 63% and 78%, respectively, in turbot (Psetta maxima) (Kroeckel et al., 2012). On the other hand, nutrient digestibility in yellow mealworm seems to be higher. For examples, Fontes et al. (2019) reported digestibility values of 85% and 91% for protein and lipid in yellow mealworm meal for Nile tilapia. A comparative study also found significantly higher nutrient digestibility of yellow mealworm in European sea bass juveniles (Basto et al., 2020). Digestibility values of protein, fat, energy, phosphorus were observed to be 89% and 76%, 95% and 91%, 79% and 67%, 83% and 36% in yellow mealworm meal and black soldier fly meal, respectively. Digestibility of essential amino acids was also higher in yellow mealworm meal (96%) than in black soldier fly meal (92%) (Basto et al., 2020). The chitin content was 4.6% and 6.1%, respectively, in yellow mealworm meal and black soldier fly meal in this comparative study (Basto et al., 2020). There seemed to be a correlation between the chitin content and the differences in nutrient digestibility. However it was also observed in the same study that defatting insect meals in general improved digestibility of nutrients while the chitin content remained similar between defatted and non-defatted insect meals (Basto et al., 2020). It appears that chitin alone cannot explain the lower nutrient digestibility in insect meals. The comparison across studies is complicated by the variable nutrient compositions of insect meals used in specific studies, fish species and experimental conditions and warrants further research.

The amino acid profiles are taxon-dependent and vary with species, with the Diptera group (true flies) demonstrating similar profiles to that of fish meal (Barroso et al., 2014; Henry et al., 2015). The amino acid profiles of black solider flies and yellow mealworms seem to be similar, but one notable difference is the lower methionine concentration in yellow mealworms (Barroso et al., 2014; Makkar et al., 2014; de Marco et al., 2015; Basto et al., 2020). On the other hand, yellow mealworms contain appreciable levels of taurine, which is beneficial for fish growth and health (Henry et al., 2015; Basto et al., 2020). It has been observed that high levels of black solider flies resulted in low taurine concentrations in diets, which might have affected lipid metabolism (Belghit et al., 2018). Amino acids profiles can be improved through processing methods, as found in the defatted insect meals (Basto et al., 2020). However, defatted yellow mealworm meal contained less taurine than non-defatted yellow mealworm meal whereas it was the opposite for black solider flies (Basto et al., 2020). This inconsistency reflects the complexity of assessing nutritive values of ingredients and warrants further research in this area.

Fatty acid profiles of insects are species-specific. The major fatty acid constituents of black soldier fly larvae are saturated fatty acids and monounsaturated fatty acids (Ewald et al., 2020). Medium-chain saturated fatty acid lauric acid (12:0) is the dominant fatty acid in black soldier fly larvae, accounting for between 13% and 52% of total fatty acids (Liland et al., 2017; Oonincx et al., 2015; Ewald et al., 2020). On the other hand, the main fatty acid in yellow mealworms is oleic acid 18:1n9 (Oonincx et al., 2015). In addition yellow mealworms contain higher linoleic acid 18:2n-6 than black soldier fly larvae (Makkar et al., 2014; Oonincx et al., 2015). The levels of long-chain polyunsaturated fatty acids, especially eicosapentaenoic (EPA) and docosahexaenoic (DHA) fatty acids are negligible in all insects (Makkar et al., 2014; Oonincx et al., 2015).

Fatty acid profiles can be manipulated by the substrates used to raise the insects and it is possible to enrich the EPA and DHA content by feeding insects with fish offal or algae (Sealey et al., 2011; Liland et al., 2017; Barroso et al., 2019 ). However, in a recent study with black soldier fly larvae by Ewald et al. (2020), it was observed that the fatty acid profiles can also be affected by the harvesting weight of larvae and the modification of the fatty acid profiles appeared to be limited. Therefore, care should be taken to ensure adequate dietary levels of EPA and DHA to meet the needs of fish. The negative effect of high levels of insect meal on growth performance may arise from the dietary deficiency in EPA and DHA to fish, even though diets are formulated to contain the same levels of dietary lipids as the fish meal control diets. It might be necessary to add fish oils to insect meal based diets to ensure sufficient amounts of EPA and DHA, as demonstrated in a study by Belghit et al. (2018) who successfully incorporated 60% black soldier fly in the diets of Atlantic salmon. Furthermore, the digestibility of lipids is significantly influenced by fatty acid profiles, especially the proportion of saturated, monounsaturated and polyunsaturated fatty acids (Hua and Bureau, 2009). Low lipid digestibility in turbot diets containing high levels of black soldier fly was attributed to the high proportion of saturated fatty acids (Kroeckel et al., 2012). Whether the differences in the effects of high levels of black solider fly meals and yellow mealworms are due to the differences in fatty acid profiles remains to be substantiated.

Meta-analysis is a useful approach to compare and synthesize results from different studies. However, it has limitations in the context of evaluating nutritive values of alternative ingredients replacing fish meal (Hua and Bureau, 2012). The meta-analysis approach is limited by screening data to ensure the comparability of experimental diets and fish meal control diets. Furthermore, comparison across studies should ideally take into account all biological and dietary factors because the issue of fish meal replacement is not a simple matter of using one substance to substitute another (fish meal versus an alternative ingredient). Therefore Hua and Bureau (2012) proposed a nutritional modeling approach as a more robust and flexible approach to assess nutritive values of ingredients. At present the application of this approach in assessing nutritive values of insect meals is impeded by the lack of sufficient information on the composition, digestibility and availability of nutrients from different types of insect meals in various fish species. Also important is a better understanding of the antinutrients and/or immunostimulants in insect meals. Insect meals present special challenges as their nutrient compositions and profiles are highly variable and dependent on substrates, developmental stages of the insects and processing methods. More research is warranted to elucidate the various factors that affect the effectiveness of the dietary inclusions of insect meals in aquaculture feeds and allow a better integration and translation of the knowledge into practical feed formulations.

5. Conclusion

With the increasing interests of incorporating insect meals in aquaculture feeds, it is critical to identify their optimal inclusion levels so that fish growth and health can be ensured. The present study employed a meta-analysis approach to quantify the relationship between fish growth performance and the inclusion level of insect meals. The results suggest that in general fish can utilize moderate levels of insect meals in their diets to support growth performance comparable to fish meal-based diets. However, the effects of high levels of insect meals seem to be largely dependent on the species of insects. While high levels of black solider fly depressed fish growth, yellow mealworm seemed to be well tolerated by fish. The results highlighted the importance of future research into the nutritive values of different insect species and the necessity to identify optimal levels for different types of insect meals. The results from this study appear to suggest that a lack of difference between full-fat and defatted black soldier fly meals in their effects on fish growth performance when diets were nutrient balanced. However, these results should be viewed as inconclusive because the delineation of the effects between full-fat and defatted black soldier fly meals is confounded by the varying degrees of defatting (partially or fully defatted meals) and the variable nutrient compositions of the insect meals. The nutrient compositions and profiles of insect meals are highly variable and dependent on substrates, developmental stages of the insects and processing methods of the insect meals. In addition, feed production technologies such as extrusion might play a role in the nutritional values of feeds containing insect meals. Ideally all these influencing factors should be taken into consideration, which was not possible in the present study due to the limited available data. This topic should be revisited later when more research has been carried out in this area. In the meantime, the results stressed the importance of ensuring the nutritional comparability of the experimental diets when evaluating the nutritive values of insect meals against fish meals. Moreover, nutritional models could be a more robust and flexible approach to assess nutritive values of ingredients by integrating various biological and dietary factors. More research is warranted to further elucidate the various factors that affect the effectiveness of the dietary inclusions of insect meal in aquaculture feed, as well as to integrate and translate this information into practical feed formulations.
